<taxonomicName id="08824D6A5C52164DF9FFFB15FF27FB23" box="[151,246,1190,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Exochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FDF6EAFB5C52164DF9FFFB15FF27FB23" box="[151,246,1190,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1">Exochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be recognized (
<bibRefCitation id="AB134B185C52164DF888FB15FD7EFB23" author="Gauld" box="[480,687,1190,1215]" pageId="1" refString="Gauld, I., Sithole, R., Gomes, J. U. &amp; Godoy, C. (2002) The Ichneumonidae of Costa Rica, 4. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 66, 1 - 768." type="journal article" year="2002">
Gauld 
<emphasis id="FDF6EAFB5C52164DFB46FB14FDB6FB23" box="[558,615,1190,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1">et al.</emphasis>
, 
<number id="794A24CE5C52164DFB1DFB14FD7EFB23" box="[629,687,1191,1215]" pageId="1" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) by an obtusely to acutely pointed projection extending upwards a little above bases of antennae, outer spur of mid tibia shorter than inner one, fore wing without an enclosed areolet, metasoma without longitudinal carinae on tergite II. This group is known to parasitize a wide range of microlepidopterous larvae in leaf rolls, but the hosts of almost all Neotropical species are unknown.
</paragraph>
